SALMONELLOSIS, SONGBIRDS - USA & CANADA
***************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
See Also
Salmonella, common redpolls - Canada 20000512002806
Date: Thursday May 18, 2000, 4:09PM
From: Andre Dallaire <dallaira@medvet.umontreal.ca>

To comment on the previous posting regarding salmonellosis in songbirds in
the province of Quebec (Canada), it is not rare to encounter occasional
cases of infection associated with Salmonella in wild birds. Unusual
features of this outbreak were the high number of birds affected and the
fact that infected/dead birds found around feeders came from a large
geographical area within the province (lower Laurentians [area north of
metropolitan Montreal but also from Montreal, Trois-RiviSres, L'Assomption
and Quebec). In addition, the bacterium was probably transmitted from
infected birds to domestic cats.
The Common Redpoll (_Carduelis flammea_) is a small songbird found in
southern Canada during winter time which usually flies back north for
breeding when summertime arrives. Dark-eyed juncos (_Junco hyemalis_),
House Finches (_Carpodacus mexicanus_) and an American Kestrel (_Falco
sparverius_) were also diagnosed with the infection. It is not completely
understood why salmonellosis pandemics occasionally occur in songbirds.
Asymptomatic carriers most likely start to excrete the bacteria when
submitted to environmental stress (sudden temperature changes, shortages of
food) and then contaminate the feeding place that other birds are using.
People usually notice sick small birds that stay put at the feeder for a
few days before death. Sick birds can be picked up by hands. Most affected
songbirds had decreased muscle mass and a fibrinonecrotizing ingluvitis
with occasional necrotic foci visible in other organs such as the spleen.
Group B _Salmonella_ was isolated in pure culture from all submitted
tissues. Most of these avian isolates were identified as _S. typhimurium_.
At the same time, veterinarians from private clinics within the Laurentian
region, north of Montreal, began receiving sick cats with anorexia, fever,
vomiting, diarrhea and occasionally with icterus. Group B Salmonella was
also isolated from 12 out of 18 fecal samples submitted from these cats.
Complete serovar identification and phagetyping of these isolates is still
pending. The zoonotic potential of having an infected cat within a
household is obvious. There have been no declared human cases as far as we
know.
--
Andre, D. Dallaire, DVM, MSc
Canadian Cooperative Wildlife Health Center - Saint-Hyacinthe branch
e-mail: dallaira@medvet.umontreal.ca
Robert Higgins, DVM, D.Sc.
Bacteriology Diagnostic Laboratory
Department of Pathology and Microbiology
Facult, de medecine veterinaire
Universit, de Montreal, Quebec

