[2
Date: Thu, 18 May 2000 18:42:02 -0500
From: Kim Miller <kim_miller@usgs.gov>

There was a recent report on ProMED-mail regarding salmonellosis in Canada.
We've had some reports in the US as well and I wanted to pass along a brief
summary to you. I will be away from my office for the next few days, if
you have any questions on the info below, please contact my colleague, Dr
Kathy Converse at <kathy_converse@usgs.gov>
--
Kim Miller
The National Wildlife Health Center (NWHC) has received reports of songbird
mortality at birdfeeders in New York, Vermont, Virginia, West Virginia,
North Carolina, Michigan, Illinois, and Georgia from other wildlife
diagnostic laboratories and private citizens. Mortality was first noted in
March with pine siskins and redpolls the primary species affected. Sick
birds were reported to perch for long periods of time with their feathers
"fluffed up".
Carcasses examined at NWHC, Southeastern Cooperative Wildlife Disease
Study, the Michigan Rose Lake Wildlife Research Center and New York Dept of
Conservation Wildlife Pathology Unit have been diagnosed with the bacterial
disease salmonellosis. _Salmonella typhimurium_, has been isolated and is
the strain commonly associated with songbird epizootics. _Salmonella_
bacteria are present in the intestines and pass out with the feces. The
bacteria can be transmitted through contact with an infected animal or
ingestion or food or water contaminated with fecal material from an
infected animal.
Salmonellosis is a common cause of songbird mortality in the US and
generally occurs as small, localized sporadic events. Occasionally
large-scale mortality occurs over a large geographic area. Most recently,
in the winter of 1998, salmonellosis mortality in goldfinch, redpolls, pine
siskins was confirmed in 16 states (primarily in the East and Midwest).
--
Kimberli J. G. Miller, DVM
Wildlife Disease Specialist
USGS
National Wildlife Health Center
6006 Schroeder Rd
Madison, WI 53711
e-mail: kim_miller@usgs.gov
